<br>
Do you remember the way we used to hold toes beneath the covers at night? My big toe would curl around yours, and every inch of our bodies would touch, making us a seamless whole. The way my body fit perfectly into the curve of yours as you told me stories by candlelight? I can hear you even now, your soft voice somehow carrying over the thundering waves just outside our window, as if the Ocean of Tears were as rapt as I to hear your voice. Is there such a thing as a silent scream? For that is what the crashing waves were: an earthquake of silence enthralled by your tale spinning. Even the ocean loved you.<br>
<br>
Do you remember the day you slipped a twisted strand of grass onto my finger, promising your heart for eternity? We played in the water that day, echoes of our childhood together, your smile unchanged, a boy’s smile on a man’s face. <br>
<br>
I loved you even when we were both toddling along in baby britches, exploring the world by putting everything and anything into our mouths. Remember the gnoll droppings? You called it candy, and somewhere in our imaginations we convinced ourselves that it WAS candy. Amazing we lived through that period, but we did, to the great relief of our parents. <br>
<br>
My heart broke the day you went to Qeynos with your father for training. Remember the letters we wrote, our love transcending the distance? Or the celebration we had upon your return? I walked bow-legged for days. Thank the gods for long skirts, or else my papa would have had your head mounted on our wall. <br>
<br>
Poor papa. You were my strength when he died, your warmth always near enough to grasp whenever I would weep. You were such a gentleman, taking mama’s arm as we said our farewells to papa and lit his bier. I remember clearly the trepidation I felt as mother watched papa’s corpse burn, the father of her children, the lover who once filled her loins with desire, as you did mine. I knew then that I never wanted to let you go. <br>
<br>
Don’t you see how much I loved you? And you loved me too! But then... well, we all make mistakes, lover, and I forgive you. We all sow our wild oats, I suppose. Well, I didn’t, but can I blame you for being young and confused? When you said you were going to marry her, you were just confused. I understand that now. I’m so glad you understand it now too. And now nothing will separate us. You have repented for your folly, and now you know that you can’t live without me. Just like I can’t live without you. <br>
<br>
Together forever, you and I.<br>
<br>
My Eternal Love,<br>
<br>
Fajera</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Fajera’s lips twitched into a small smile as she blew the ink dry on the curling parchment. Her eyes captured the light of the candle, glinting with love and remembrance. The door scraped open behind her, and her smile broadened as she stood and turned. “Lover! You’re back early. I hope you finished all my errands! I was missing you so much I decided to write you a letter. Shall I read it to you?” The door creaked to a close, sending a woosh of fresh air into the dusty chamber. Fajera reached out to stroke her lover’s face, beaming brightly at him. Her lover stared vacantly back, his empty eye sockets seeming to swallow the dim candlelight, leaving the room cold and dark. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fajera>Fajera</A> at: 10/6/03 7:36 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nedagda@firionavie>Nedagda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/30/03 10:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1160.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Dear Lover</span><hr size=1> Ok, the story got me.  I'm enjoying it even if it seems yer an evil type.......keep 'em coming.<br>
