<br>
The first time she had called him Lover had been a warm, rainy morning. They couldn't have been more than eight summers old. Ten years past, now. Seems like an eternity. They were playing beneath the dock next to the inn where they boarded under Uncle Lunce's care while Papa was out at sea. Mama cleaned the inn and worked in the kitchens beside the cook, helping Uncle make the inn a cozy, hospitable place. <br>
<br>
That day in particular, Tobias Fireheart had snuck away from his chores at his father's smithy to catch crabs with Fajera, her squealing as they skittered out of the sand and he swooped them up in a bucket. They had retreated to the shelter of the dock when the rain was the heaviest, the rising sea water not a concern to immortal youth. He played the fisherman coming home with his catch, and she busied herself &quot;sweeping&quot; the wet sand at her bare feet. And, echoing her mother's words when Papa swept in from the sea, she exclaimed, &quot;About time, Lover mine!&quot; when Fisherman Tobias first entered the &quot;door&quot; of their playhouse under the dock. From that day on, the name stuck like wet sand between the toes.<br>
<br>
But now, the way Lover resisted meeting her eyes sent a shiver down her spine. Even when they argued, his way was to hammer out a solution face to face, eye to eye. Her brow crumpled with worry as he took a seat by the fire, not even removing his boots to stay a while. <br>
<br>
&quot;I made soup,&quot; she said softly, kissing his cheek gently before retrieving two bowls from the sideboard.  <p><i>Lover and I went down to the fair, <br>
