<br>
Fajera sent messages as often as she could, and not a day went by that there wasn't something waiting for him at the Ironforge estate. Sometimes a letter, sometimes a trinket from their childhood, and sometimes a once-worn article of clothing for him to smell and hold as he slept. He was a man in love, sickeningly, pathetically, hopelessly, marvelously in love. He had been since childhood, and he loved it. <br>
<br>
But somewhere in the periphery of his apprentice work at the forge, Myrielle Ironforge had taken a liking to him. By this time, father was already back in Freeport, running their own forge. Had father been there, maybe Tobias wouldn't have been quite so lonely; maybe he wouldn't have been caught unaware. But father had his own business to run, so he wasn't there the day Myrielle finally made her first move. <br>
