<br>
Now, as Tobias shared the news with Fajera, his only feeling was shame. Shame for betraying his beautiful Fajera, shame for giving in to his urges, shame for buckling to his father's demands. <br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
&quot;But Tobias, what about us? What about OUR family? Please, Tobias. Please. What about us?&quot; Fajera's voice cracked like bone as she clung to the back of a chair, the drying laundry billowing behind her in the ocean breeze coming in gusts through the window. <br>
<br>
This couldn't be happening. No, this was impossible. Mistress Darkbriar had promised they would always be together. Fajera searched her memory for an alternate understanding of Opal's prophecy and found none. <br>
<br>
After Fajera's father died, she had spent weeks questioning the meaning of life and death. She had wandered from Priest to Priestess, seeking answers to dark questions stirring in her soul. Why did some live, while others die? She could not stand to lose Lover, not ever, for any reason, but especially death. Would Lover die while she was doomed to live without him? All the answers given by various faiths were unsatisfactory, save one. For the price of her eternal service, Innoruuk, Prince of Hate, would answer her prayers. <br>
<br>
The words of the prophecy came drifting back to her now, as her gaze lingered on the shaggy auburn of Tobias's downturned head. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Your love will be transformed, replaced by an even greater power, binding you to him and he to you for all eternity. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Eternal service seemed a small price to pay to spend eternity with Lover, for how difficult could that service be with Lover at her side? She was initiated not long after speaking with Opal Darkbriar, becoming a follower of Hate for the sake of Love. Little did she know the price Innoruuk would exact. <br>
<br>
But now, with the threat of losing Tobias so real, Fajera shook her head, her lips moving wordlessly in disbelief. &quot;No, no, Lover. You can't leave me. The prophecy... the prophecy...&quot; she stammered, her eyes wide and crazed.<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
Tobias raised his head and the firelight glinted off his wet cheeks. &quot;Prophecy? What prophecy? Fajera, what are you talking about?&quot; he asked, his tears for the moment forgotten in his confusion. Was his love having a nervous breakdown?<br>
<br>
&quot;Fajera, what is wrong with you?&quot; he said softly, rising to steady her tottering form.<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
Somewhere in her mind, Fajera heard Tobias's voice, but even louder was the voiceless command that throbbed in her head. &quot;Serve me now and the prophecy will be fulfilled.&quot; She listened to the silent voice, nodding as she digested each word, pushing Tobias gently away as he reached for her. <br>
<br>
Then, her mind clouded by the power of the silent voice, she obeyed, taking the knife from its place in the bread, and stabbing it directly into the wide, blue orb calling her name. Again and again, hot liquid gushing onto her face, Lover's screams muted by the silent voice, stabbing, stabbing, obeying.<br>
<br>
Then all went dark.<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
When Fajera awoke from her trance, she lay bundled in a blanket in Neriak Foreign Quarter. She immediately looked for Lover and found him standing near the fire, staring at the dancing flames. She spoke to him, but he didn't answer, and a terrible chill raced through her bones. <br>
<br>
Tobias looked pale, with dark rings beneath his lovely blue eyes, his auburn hair a shaggy mess, but he was alive, and he was with her, and that was all that mattered. Lover had lost much of his ability to speak in his illness, responding only to her, and even then only to confirm her requests. And he called her Master, which irritated her to no end, but Perrir said that was simply his way of saying thank you now that speaking was so difficult to him. <br>
<br>
And Fajera processed each inconsistency in her own way, only accepting information that confirmed her worldview: That Lover was ill, but alive, and that they were together forever. She hoped in his recovery from this strange illness, blaming it on his time in the storm the night they had their big fight. But to Fajera, he was still Tobias, still Lover, handsome and vital, just ill. <br>
<br>
To everyone else, he was a fleshless horror, a pile of living bones. <p><i>Lover and I went down to the fair, <br>
